These are little changes that a new player might not notice or think to try, but that go a long way to making the game more flexible and less frustrating before you've mastered it.

5) Speaking of the lazy man's parry, enemies are much easier to stagger in Elden Ring--by doing enough damage over a sustained period of time, even most bosses will just stagger and give you an attempt to do a parry-style riposte/visceral attack. Again, huge hurt with low effort.

4) Guard counters. These are not explained super well in my experience, but if you press R2 immediately after an enemy attack bounces off your shield, you do a heavy-hitting counterattack. It's a lazy man's parry. It's lovely.

3) Spirit ashes. Fast travel to the Church of Ella after you get to the Hold; you can get an item that lets you summon spirit ashes, little findable friends who will help you fight. This can seem superfluous, but it is hella stacked actually; these little friends help.

2) Status effects! Perceptually, compared to prior games in this ouevre, big enemies and bosses are way, way more susceptible to status effects. Bleed, poison; by figuring out what works and marshaling your resources, you can do lots of real damage.

1) Summoning Pools. Near major conflict areas, you can find little statues with arms stretched wide. If you interact with them, they activate a local hub for summoning signs. That means, if you need help, find the nearest pool--it's where people are most likely to put summons.
